# Error: Table Not Created After Adding @CreationTimestamp and @UpdateTimestamp

## Scenario

I had a Spring Boot + JPA + Hibernate project.

Initially my entity looked like this:

```java
private LocalDateTime createOn;

private LocalDateTime updateOn;
```

Application started successfully and table was created.

Then I added automatic timestamp annotations:

```java
@CreationTimestamp
private LocalDateTime createOn;

@UpdateTimestamp
private LocalDateTime updateOn;
```

After this, table creation failed.

---

# Error Message

```text
Error executing DDL

create table posts(
 create_on datetime(6),
 update_on datetime(6)
)

SQL syntax error near '(6)'
```

---

# What I Thought Initially

I thought:

```text
@CreationTimestamp is wrong
OR
@UpdateTimestamp is wrong
```

But that was NOT the actual problem.

---

# Actual Root Cause

To understand this, first see what these annotations do.

## Step 1 — What @CreationTimestamp does

```java
@CreationTimestamp
private LocalDateTime createOn;
```

Meaning:

```text
When INSERT happens
Hibernate automatically stores current timestamp
```

Example:

Before save:

```text
title = Java
createOn = null
```

After save:

```text
title = Java
createOn = 2026-06-19 15:30
```

No manual setting required.

---

## Step 2 — What @UpdateTimestamp does

```java
@UpdateTimestamp
private LocalDateTime updateOn;
```

Meaning:

```text
Whenever UPDATE happens
Hibernate automatically changes update time
```

Example:

Before update:

```text
updateOn = 15:30
```

After update:

```text
updateOn = 15:45
```

---

# Where the Actual Problem Happened

My field type was:

```java
LocalDateTime
```

Hibernate saw:

```text
LocalDateTime
```

and internally converted it into SQL type:

```sql
datetime(6)
```

Generated SQL:

```sql
create table posts(
 create_on datetime(6),
 update_on datetime(6)
)
```

---

# What is datetime(6)?

```text
DATETIME
+
microseconds precision
```

Example:

Normal DATETIME:

```text
2026-06-19 15:30:10
```

datetime(6):

```text
2026-06-19 15:30:10.123456
```

That `(6)` stores extra precision.

---

# Why Table Creation Failed

My database version/configuration did not support:

```sql
datetime(6)
```

So database rejected SQL.

Flow:

```text
Entity
↓
Hibernate generated SQL
↓
Database rejected datetime(6)
↓
DDL failed
↓
Table not created
```

---

# Solution 1 (Worked for Me)

Force Hibernate to use normal DATETIME.

```java
@CreationTimestamp
@Column(columnDefinition="DATETIME")
private LocalDateTime createOn;

@UpdateTimestamp
@Column(columnDefinition="DATETIME")
private LocalDateTime updateOn;
```

---

# What This Fix Actually Does

Before:

```text
Hibernate:
I will choose datatype

Result:
datetime(6)
```

After:

```text
Developer:
Use DATETIME only

Result:
DATETIME
```

Generated SQL:

```sql
create_on DATETIME
update_on DATETIME
```

Table created successfully.

---

# Solution 2 (Advanced / Modern Database)

If database supports datetime precision:

```java
@CreationTimestamp
private LocalDateTime createOn;

@UpdateTimestamp
private LocalDateTime updateOn;
```

No extra annotation needed.

---

# Solution 3 (Dialect Configuration)

application.properties

```properties
spring.jpa.database-platform=org.hibernate.dialect.MySQLDialect
```

Meaning:

```text
Tell Hibernate:
Generate SQL suitable for MySQL
```

---

# Final Learning

The problem was NOT:

```text
@CreationTimestamp
@UpdateTimestamp
```

The actual issue was:

```text
Hibernate generated SQL datatype
≠
Database supported datatype
```

Always check generated SQL logs.

---

# Interview Explanation

“I faced table creation failure after adding audit timestamp annotations. Hibernate converted LocalDateTime into datetime(6), but my database configuration did not support that precision. I fixed it by controlling SQL datatype generation using @Column(columnDefinition='DATETIME') and proper Hibernate configuration.”
